description:
Learn how to use Cursor AI as we compare it to Claude Code in this detailed Claude Code vs Cursor breakdown. From Plan Mode and slash commands to browser automation and DeepLinks, discover the best AI coding experience for developers in 2025.

In this Cursor AI tutorial, we explore everything new in Cursor—from Plan Mode and slash commands to the improved browser automation agent. This Cursor tutorial breaks down real workflows showing how Claude Code vs Cursor stacks up in 2025, including stability, integrations, and usability. You’ll also see how Cursor MCP, DeepLinks, and background agents compare to Codex vs Cursor, and even how Windsurf vs Cursor feels in day-to-day dev use. Whether you’re curious about Cursor AI free unlimited access, Cursor free features, or using Cursor Obsidian setup tricks, this video covers it all.

For those exploring how to use Cursor AI or how to use Cursor efficiently with MCP servers, this guide shows how Cursor bridges visual coding and automation. It’s ideal for AI coding enthusiasts, from beginners to power users, comparing Cursor vs Claude Code performance and usability.

This is a part of our vibe coding series exploring AI tools like Claude Code, Google AI Studio, Open AI, and Lovable, helping developers create faster with artificial intelligence. Whether you’re into starter story workflows, coding, or advanced agent setups, this walkthrough gives you everything you need to master Cursor today.

comments.text: You just need one, Cursor and yeah that's it. Auto mode is literally unlimited, and you still have $20 to use if you need to use Claude models or any other without Auto mode. With Auto mode, the usage is stopped, meaning it is using that unlimited pool and not the $20 credits that you paid for. Auto is also excellent I believe for most tasks it does use high quality models as when switching I actually did not see much difference in quality between both modes. Overall, for a heavy coder like me Cursor is the way to go as the 5-hour limit for Claude code is just not enough.

comments.text:
🎯 Key points for quick navigation:

00:00 ⚖️ The video argues Cursor has closed the gap with Claude Code and added new features that shift the balance.
00:14 😲 The creator recently re-tested Cursor after a long gap and was surprised by how much it improved.
00:56 🧭 Cursor added Plan Mode (follow-up Qs → detailed plan → implement) similar to Claude Code.
01:24 ⌨️ Cursor now supports slash commands / custom command files (compatible with Claude Code commands).
01:53 🛡️ Local dev: much better background server/terminal reliability and sandboxed terminals to protect the host.
02:23 🤖 Multi-agent support: manage multiple agents, run background agents, and integrate with Slack/GitHub/Linear; native git worktree support.
03:19 🧠 Context & memory: Cursor shows context usage and added summarize/compact commands to manage long sessions.
04:00 🔗 Hooks & CLI: Cursor added pre/post tool hooks and a CLI; hooks can prevent dangerous operations.
05:40 🌐 Native browser automation (Playwright): navigate, click, take screenshots, read console/network — agent can test apps and auto-fix code.
07:44 🔔 Workflow niceties: agent autocomplete, menu-bar monitoring, OS notifications, and deep links that open prompts directly.
08:56 🎨 Usability win: Cursor’s visual UI (ready-made MCP.json, visual editors) is much easier for non-terminal users than Claude Code.
10:35 ⚡ Auto mode intelligently selects models to save tokens and is efficient for most tasks.
10:48 💸 Pricing tradeoffs: Cursor’s usage-based $20 model vs Claude Code’s timed access windows — each has pros/cons for heavy devs.
11:58 ✅ Practical recommendation: subscribe to both — use Claude for very large/complex jobs and Cursor (auto mode) for ~90% of routine work.
12:13 🎬 Bottom line: recent browser automation + stability/usability improvements make Cursor a competitive, production-ready option.
